The White House announced additional guests who will be seated in the First Lady's box during the State of the Union Address. These guests represent stories of Americans who are working hard to improve their communities and their own economic outcomes. Some of the guests include Misty DeMars, who lost her job and is struggling without unemployment insurance, and Peter Mouskondis, the CEO of a family-owned foodservice distribution company that emphasizes work-life balance for its employees. Other guests include Cory Remsburg, an Army Ranger who was injured in Afghanistan, and Estiven Rodriguez, a high school student who is a first-generation college student. The list also includes individuals such as a pizza restaurant CEO and a kitchen worker, a survivor of the Boston Marathon bombing, a teacher, and the CEO of General Motors.